🧾 PROFESSIONAL VERSION (For Comparison After You Finish)

Below is the same prompt rewritten in a more formal, production-style specification format.

Software Design Exercise
Title: Interface-Driven Payment Processing Framework
Objective

Design and implement a modular payment processing framework that demonstrates proper application of:

Interface-based abstraction

Abstract classes

Runtime polymorphism

Loose coupling and extensibility

System Overview

The application must support multiple payment mechanisms through a common abstraction layer. Each payment method should encapsulate its own processing behavior while conforming to a shared contract.

The design must ensure:

Open/Closed Principle compliance

No dependency on concrete implementations

Polymorphic behavior at runtime

Functional Requirements
1. Payment Contract

Define an interface PaymentMethod that declares:

void processPayment(double amount)

void refund(double amount)

String getPaymentDetails()

2. Abstract Base Layer

Define an abstract class AbstractPayment that:

Implements PaymentMethod

Contains a protected transactionFee attribute

Provides a concrete helper method:
double calculateFinalAmount(double amount)

Declares processPayment() as abstract

3. Concrete Implementations

Provide at minimum three concrete implementations:

CreditCardPayment

PayPalPayment

CryptoPayment

At least one implementation must extend AbstractPayment.

Each class must:

Maintain relevant identifying attributes

Provide custom behavior for processing and refunding

Apply transaction fees appropriately

4. Payment Execution Layer

Create a PaymentProcessor class containing:

public void executeTransaction(PaymentMethod paymentMethod, double amount)


This method must operate solely against the PaymentMethod abstraction and demonstrate runtime polymorphism.

No type-checking or conditional branching based on implementation class is permitted.

5. Demonstration Layer

Provide a Main class that:

Instantiates multiple implementations

Stores them in a List<PaymentMethod>

Iterates and executes transactions

Evaluation Criteria

Correct use of abstraction

Proper interface-driven architecture

Elimination of tight coupling

Clear demonstration of polymorphism

Code readability and extensibility